    <center><table class="itemDisplayTable">
<tr><td class="metadataFieldLabel">Title:&nbsp;</td><td class="metadataFieldValue">Study of Probiotic and Antibacterial Activity and Characterization of</td></tr>
<tr><td class="metadataFieldLabel">Authors:&nbsp;</td><td class="metadataFieldValue">Ilayaraja.R</td></tr>
<tr><td class="metadataFieldLabel">Keywords:&nbsp;</td><td class="metadataFieldValue">Probiotic<br />Human Breast Milk</td></tr>
<tr><td class="metadataFieldLabel">Issue Date:&nbsp;</td><td class="metadataFieldValue">Mar-2012 </td></tr>
<tr><td class="metadataFieldLabel">Publisher:&nbsp;</td><td class="metadataFieldValue">SRM University</td></tr>
<tr><td class="metadataFieldLabel">Series/Report no.:&nbsp;</td><td class="metadataFieldValue">T0089</td></tr>
<tr><td class="metadataFieldLabel">Abstract:&nbsp;</td><td class="metadataFieldValue">Breast milk is a primary food for an infant. 419 bacterial strains
were isolated from 450 samples of breast milk. Of these 74% belonged
to Lactobacillus spp.. 311 Lactobacillus strains were identified to the
species level. The isolates of Lactobacillus strains belonged to four
species namely L.acidophillus (25%), L.fermentum (30%), L.reuteri
(27%) and L.gasseri (18%).
The CFNS of Lactobacillus strains showed inhibitory activity
against all clinical pathogens tested except Streptococcus sps. The
bacteriocin activity was completely inactivated by only proteolytic
enzymes suggesting proteinaceous nature of the bacteriocin. This
activity was not affected by the pH ranging from 2 to 11 and during
storage for up to 100 days at -200C and 40C.
The Bacteriocin was purified by precipitated with 40 to 60 % of
ammonium sulphate, followed by dialysis and Ion – exchange
chromatography. The purified bacteriocin had broad spectrum of
activity. SDS-PAGE analysis showed that the bacteriocin of L.reuteri
was a peptide with low molecular weight of 2.5 kDa, L.acidophillus 5.6
kDa, L.gasseri 4.0 kDa and that of L.fermentum was 4.5kDa. The
Lactobacillus strains after treatment with ethidium bromide completely
lost its antibacterial activity, indicating that the bacteriocin was plasmid
encoded. The protein was estimated by Bradford method. The protein
content of purified bacteriocin of L.fermentum was 32.4 μg/ml,
L.reuteri 29.41, L.acidophillus 27.9 and L.gasseri 23.52 μg/ml.
L.acidophillus, L.fermentum and L.reuteri were viable upto 120
mins of incubation with gastric juice, while L.gasseri was less tolerant
to gastric juice. The viability of L.fermentum showed the maximum
tolerance (85%) at pH 3.0, followed by L.reuteri (82%), L.acidophillus
(78%) and L.gasseri (58%). L.fermentum and L.reuteri strains showed
the highest tolerance to 2% bile concentration (98% and 94%).
L.acidophillus and L.gasseri were less tolerant to bile with survival
percentage of 89%. All the 4 Lactobacillus strains tolerated temperature
ranging from 25-450C but poorly at 150C; they tolerated up to 3% NaCl
concentration. None of Lactobacillus strains was affected by Lysozyme,
indicating that they could survive passage through the upper part of the
gastrointestinal tract and retain their probiotic action. All the strains
were susceptible to most of the antibiotics tested except Vancomycin,
Tetracycline and Kanamycin. Resistance to Vancomycin seems to be an
inherent property of Lactobacilli. They were non hemolytic on sheep
blood agar. Absence of hemolytic activity is one of the selection criteria
for starter strain for dairy and pharmaceutical uses, thus indicating the
non-virulent nature of the Lactobacillus. All species of Lactobacillus
had good viability after 6 weeks of storage at -200C and 40C. This high
viability during storage under freezing conditions makes Lactobacillus
as a promising probiotic. Co aggregation is a good characteristic of
Lactobacillus strains that can force the target cells into closer contact.
Co aggregation of L.fermentum with MRSA was 86.5% and with
Ps.aeruginosa was 82.5% and it was the highest compared to other
Lactobacillus species. All Lactobacillus strains showed an increased
production of EPS with raise in temperature from 300C through 370C to
450C, and increasing pH from 4 to 7. EPS production of these strains
reached maximum after 18 hrs during exponential phase of growth.
L.fermentum and L.reuteri strains produced a high level of lactic acid
x
compared to L.acidophillus and L.gasseri. This is also a good
characteristic of a probiotic.
This study highlights the value of Lactobacilli of human breast
milk. Bacteriocin produced by Lactobacilli proved to be an ideal
antibacterial substance. The Lactobacilli possess all the features
characteristic of an ideal probiotic. Thus addition of Lactobacilli
(Probiotic) or its products (bacteriocin) to infants’ formula could be a
new alternative to mimic some of the beneficial effects of human milk
in children, who are not breast fed. Thus Lactobacillus Strains can be
considered as potential biotherapeutic agents.</td></tr>
<tr><td class="metadataFieldLabel">URI:&nbsp;</td><td class="metadataFieldValue"><a href="http://hdl.handle.net/123456789/9292">http://hdl.handle.net/123456789/9292</a></td></tr>
